    "1656049353eec351e4": {
      "type": "loop-article-richtext",
      "blocks": {
        "5c77ffdf-ef23-42e9-a417-5cd536e47d37": {
          "type": "heading",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "Keeping safe on the roads: our top motorcycle safety tips",
            "heading_size": "h2"
          }
        },
        "165604935313dd40c2-0": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>Pure exhilaration. Adrenaline pumping. An incomparable feeling of freedom.<\/p><p>These are all emotions that motorcyclists experience on a daily basis.<\/p><p>Coupled with the reality that they’re cheaper to run, cheaper to insure and faster than most other on-road vehicles, motorcycle driving is an attractive option.<\/p><p>But it’s also true that riding a motorcycle can be dangerous. In fact, motorcycle riders are 40 times more likely to be injured than car drivers. It’s important to look after yourself on the roads so you can enjoy the ride and be safe at the same time.<\/p><p>This guide is going to give you the top motorcycle riding tips, so you can be aware of the dangers and take precautions.<\/p>"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "5c77ffdf-ef23-42e9-a417-5cd536e47d37",
        "165604935313dd40c2-0"
      ],
      "settings": {
        "desktop_content_position": "left",
        "content_alignment": "left",
        "color_scheme": "#ffffff",
        "full_width": true,
        "padding_top": 40,
        "padding_bottom": 52
      }
    },
    "a077ccac-c571-4ae0-9d42-69f29fe3f817": {
      "type": "image-with-text",
      "blocks": {
        "template--15787414028484__a077ccac-c571-4ae0-9d42-69f29fe3f817-16699933130b5b1837-0": {
          "type": "heading",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "1. Get The Proper Gear",
            "heading_size": "h2"
          }
        },
        "template--15787414028484__a077ccac-c571-4ae0-9d42-69f29fe3f817-16699933130b5b1837-1": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>The first step for how to ride a motorcycle safely, is investing in a solid helmet. A helmet is a non-negotiable. You need to make sure that it fits tightly and isn’t too loose, but is still comfortable. Also, it shouldn’t obstruct your vision but should still offer protection all the way around, covering your chin in case you hit the road.<\/p>",
            "text_style": "body"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "template--15787414028484__a077ccac-c571-4ae0-9d42-69f29fe3f817-16699933130b5b1837-0",
        "template--15787414028484__a077ccac-c571-4ae0-9d42-69f29fe3f817-16699933130b5b1837-1"
      ],
      "settings": {
        "image": "shopify:\/\/shop_images\/Person_Wearing_A_Motorcyle_Helmet.jpg",
        "image_3": "shopify:\/\/shop_images\/Person_Wearing_A_Motorcyle_Helmet.jpg",
        "height": "small",
        "desktop_image_width": "medium",
        "image_property": "cover",
        "layout": "image_first",
        "desktop_content_position": "top",
        "desktop_content_alignment": "left",
        "content_layout": "no-overlap",
        "color_scheme": "background-1",
        "mobile_content_alignment": "left",
        "padding_top": 36,
        "padding_bottom": 36
      }
    },
    "16560464437d7fe44b": {
      "type": "loop-article-richtext",
      "blocks": {
        "1656046443b1b2d9f5-0": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>There’s also a very good reason that a lot of riders wear leather: it’s super strong and will help to protect your skin from the floor.<br\/><br\/>When you’re riding a motorcycle, you’re not protected from small objects like stones. And even a small stone can sting if it hits you when you’re travelling at 60mph. No one wants that.<\/p>"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "1656046443b1b2d9f5-0"
      ],
      "settings": {
        "desktop_content_position": "left",
        "content_alignment": "left",
        "color_scheme": "#ffffff",
        "full_width": true,
        "padding_top": 40,
        "padding_bottom": 52
      }
    },
    "16560502492171dd33": {
      "type": "loop-article-richtext",
      "blocks": {
        "a6ecf790-2196-47dc-8765-ef071f39f93a": {
          "type": "heading",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "2.Check The Weather Reports",
            "heading_size": "h2"
          }
        },
        "16560502493ef96db8-0": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>Riding a bike in the rain is far more dangerous than riding in a car. If you’re getting ready to go for a ride, make sure you check the weather report for any signs of snow, ice or heavy rain.<br\/><br\/>If you have to travel in heavy rain, try to avoid doing so right after the storm starts. When rain first hits a road it can bring up oil and make the road slippery. But if you wait for a while, the rain will wash away the oil and it will be much safer.<\/p>"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "a6ecf790-2196-47dc-8765-ef071f39f93a",
        "16560502493ef96db8-0"
      ],
      "settings": {
        "desktop_content_position": "left",
