        "full_width": true,
        "padding_top": 40,
        "padding_bottom": 52
      }
    },
    "2b05cc63-f58f-4a52-b4b1-a1a68d282df6": {
      "type": "image-with-text",
      "blocks": {
        "template--15787414028484__2b05cc63-f58f-4a52-b4b1-a1a68d282df6-166999406493e260cb-0": {
          "type": "heading",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "4. Always Leave Enough Space",
            "heading_size": "h2"
          }
        },
        "template--15787414028484__2b05cc63-f58f-4a52-b4b1-a1a68d282df6-166999406493e260cb-1": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>One of the biggest mistakes riders make is not leaving enough space between them and the vehicles around them.<br\/><br\/>Anti-lock brakes are still relatively new on bikes, so it means many bikes can’t stop as quickly as cars.<br\/><br\/>The main rule of thumb is to leave a three second gap between you and the vehicle in front. If it’s raining, add a couple more as this can increase your stopping distance by at least double.<\/p>",
            "text_style": "body"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "template--15787414028484__2b05cc63-f58f-4a52-b4b1-a1a68d282df6-166999406493e260cb-0",
        "template--15787414028484__2b05cc63-f58f-4a52-b4b1-a1a68d282df6-166999406493e260cb-1"
